SCHOOLS are reopening on Tuesday, 19 July and villagers are stressing over how their kids will get to school. This is because scholar transport was stopped, allegedly without a notice. Parents in Tloonane Village, North West, said they will now have to pay for transport from their own pockets, even though they’re struggling and most of them depend on grants. A parent said: “My child has to pay R20 a day and I’m not working. “We rely on a grant, and there’s no other income.” ALSO READ | Mzansi TAVERNS in fear The parents said scholar transport was stopped on 23 April. “We were told that the people who were transporting our children were not paid by the North West Department of Education. We wish this issue could be resolved soon because it’s taxing for many parents,” said another parent. Parents said they met the officials from the department and were told the issue would soon be resolved. One scholar transport owner said it was difficult to run a business without being paid. . Boitshoko Moremi from North West Department of Community Safety and Transport said they will look into it.